      "id": "exam1_q29",
      "question": "Which of the following is the correct way to specify a Node Affinity rule that schedules a Pod only on nodes with a label tier=frontend?",
      "multiSelect": false,
      "answers": [
        {
          "text": "Using tier=frontend directly under spec.containers in the Pod specification",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "explanation": "Specifying tier=frontend directly under spec.containers would be a syntax error and wouldn't accomplish any form of node affinity.",
          "id": "A"
        },
        {
          "text": "Using nodeAffinity within nodeSelector field in the Pod specification",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "explanation": "Node Affinity and nodeSelector are different fields in the Pod specification. nodeAffinity is generally more expressive than nodeSelector and they are not nested within each other.",
          "id": "B"
        },
        {
          "text": "Using requiredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution within affinity.nodeAffinity in the Pod specification",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "explanation": "Using requiredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution within affinity.nodeAffinity allows you to specify Node Affinity rules that must be met for a Pod to be scheduled onto a Node. The requiredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution field indicates that the rule is \"required\" when the scheduler is placing the pod but is \"ignored\" if the conditions are no longer met during execution. This means that the Pod will only be scheduled on nodes that have the label tier=frontend.",
          "id": "C"
        },
        {
          "text": "Using preferredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution within nodeSelector in the Pod specification",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "explanation": "Using preferredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution within nodeSelector is incorrect for two reasons. First, preferredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution is not a valid field for nodeSelector. Second, even if it were within affinity.nodeAffinity, \"preferred\" means that the scheduler will try to enforce the rules but will not guarantee them, so the Pod might still be scheduled on nodes that do not have the tier=frontend label.",
          "id": "D"
        }
      ],
      "source": "Mock Exam 1",
      "domain": "Container Orchestration"
