      "id": "exam4_q18",
      "question": "You are managing a cloud-native application that runs on Kubernetes in a public cloud. Recently, your team has noticed a significant increase in cloud costs, which seems to be driven by over-provisioned resources (e.g., CPU, memory) and inefficient workload scaling. You need to implement cost management strategies to reduce expenses without compromising application performance. Which of the following is the best strategy for managing costs in this Kubernetes environment?",
      "multiSelect": false,
      "answers": [
        {
          "text": "Disable resource limits in Kubernetes and rely on the cloud provider’s auto-scaling capabilities to dynamically adjust resources based on traffic.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "explanation": "Disabling resource limits in Kubernetes would lead to unpredictable behavior, as workloads could consume excessive resources, causing performance degradation or even system outages. Cloud provider auto-scaling features are helpful but do not replace Kubernetes’ built-in resource management capabilities. This approach would likely increase costs due to unregulated resource usage.",
          "id": "A"
        },
        {
          "text": "Implement the Kubernetes Vertical Pod Autoscaler (VPA) to automatically adjust the resource requests of running pods based on actual resource usage over time.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "explanation": "The Kubernetes Vertical Pod Autoscaler (VPA) is designed to optimize the resource requests for pods by adjusting them based on actual resource usage patterns. By dynamically resizing the resources of running pods, VPA can prevent over-provisioning and underutilization, leading to significant cost savings while maintaining application performance. VPA is one of the best practices for cost optimization in Kubernetes.",
          "id": "B"
        },
        {
          "text": "Set fixed resource requests and limits for all pods, ensuring that they are always allocated the maximum resources needed during peak load.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "explanation": "Setting fixed resource requests and limits based on peak usage leads to over-provisioning, which can significantly increase cloud costs. It is important to balance resource allocation based on average or typical usage rather than worst-case scenarios. This approach does not optimize resource usage, resulting in wasted capacity and higher expenses.",
          "id": "C"
        },
        {
          "text": "Use Kubernetes Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (HPA) to automatically scale up pods based on memory usage and scale down based on CPU usage to reduce costs.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "explanation": "While the Kubernetes Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (HPA) is useful for scaling pods, it is not effective for cost management if you scale up and down based on different metrics like memory and CPU usage. Scaling based on memory and CPU requires consistent monitoring, and setting contradictory metrics can lead to inefficient scaling. Additionally, HPA focuses on pod replication rather than optimizing the resource usage of individual pods.",
          "id": "D"
        }
      ],
