      "id": "exam9_q18",
      "question": "You have applied a taint to a Kubernetes node to ensure only certain workloads will run on this node. Additionally, you add a toleration to a web-app pod to match the taint so it can be scheduled on the node. However, you notice that the pod is NOT running on the desired node, and is running on a different node in the cluster.",
      "multiSelect": false,
      "answers": [
        {
          "text": "Why didn't the taint and toleration configuration ensure the pod is scheduled on the desired node?",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "explanation": "See the correct answer for more details.",
          "id": "A"
        },
        {
          "text": "taints and tolerations don't work until after the pods have been scheduled and are running",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "explanation": "Taints and tolerations in Kubernetes are mechanisms used during the scheduling process to determine which pods can be placed on which nodes. They are evaluated during the scheduling process before the pod is actually running. Therefore, taints and tolerations do work during the scheduling phase, not after the pods have already been scheduled and are running.",
          "id": "B"
        },
        {
          "text": "taints and tolerations are only used for master/control plane nodes, not for general workloads scheduled on worker nodes",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "explanation": "Taints and tolerations in Kubernetes are not limited to master/control plane nodes; they can be used on any node in the cluster to control pod placement. They are commonly used to ensure that specific workloads are scheduled on designated nodes based on the tolerations specified in the pod's configuration. Therefore, taints and tolerations are not exclusive to master/control plane nodes and can be utilized for general workloads scheduled on worker nodes as well.",
          "id": "C"
        },
        {
          "text": "you should have configured the pod with a taint and the node with the toleration",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "explanation": "In Kubernetes, taints are applied to nodes to repel certain pods, while tolerations are applied to pods to attract them to specific nodes with matching tolerations. In this scenario, the taint should be on the node, and the toleration should be on the pod to ensure that the pod is scheduled on the desired node. Swapping the configuration between the pod and the node will not achieve the desired result.",
          "id": "D"
        },
        {
          "text": "taints and tolerations do not tell a pod to go to a particular node, they only tell the nodes that they can accept pods with certain tolerations",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "explanation": "Taints and tolerations in Kubernetes are used to control which pods can be scheduled on which nodes based on the tolerations specified in the pod's configuration. They do not directly instruct a pod to run on a specific node, but rather inform the nodes that they can accept pods with specific tolerations. Therefore, the presence of a toleration in a pod does not guarantee that the pod will be scheduled on a particular node.",
          "id": "E"
        }
      ],
      "source": "Mock Exam 9",
      "domain": "Container Orchestration"
