      "id": "exam9_q27",
      "question": "When comparing push-based and pull-based deployment approaches, what is the primary difference between the two?",
      "multiSelect": false,
      "answers": [
        {
          "text": "Pull-based deployment approach requires that you provide cluster credentials to external systems, creating a potential security risk",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "explanation": "The pull-based deployment approach does not require providing cluster credentials to external systems. Instead, the cluster itself retrieves changes from a specified source. This reduces the potential security risk associated with sharing cluster credentials with external systems, making pull-based deployments a more secure option.",
          "id": "A"
        },
        {
          "text": "Push-based deployments require integration with an external system that has direct access to the Kubernetes cluster, while pull-based deployments apply changes from within the cluster itself",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "explanation": "Push-based deployments involve an external system initiating the deployment process by pushing changes directly to the Kubernetes cluster. This external system needs direct access to the cluster to apply the changes. In contrast, pull-based deployments have the cluster itself pull changes from a specified source, such as a Git repository, eliminating the need for external systems to have direct access.",
          "id": "B"
        },
        {
          "text": "Pull-based deployment approach retrieves changes directly from a Git repo, while push-based approaches rely more on manual triggers and updates",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "explanation": "This statement is incorrect because pull-based deployments don't inherently require retrieving changes directly from a Git repository; they use agents or controllers to pull updates from a central source, which can be a Git repository or an artifact registry. Additionally, push-based deployments do not necessarily rely on manual triggers — they can be automated through CI/CD pipelines where a deployment server initiates the push to target systems. The key distinction is who initiates the deployment, not whether it is manual or automated.",
          "id": "C"
        },
        {
          "text": "Push-based deployments tend to be more secure since they don't require exposing any credentials to an external system to provide direct access to the Kubernetes cluster",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "explanation": "Push-based deployments may require exposing credentials to external systems to allow them to directly access the Kubernetes cluster and push changes. This exposure of credentials can pose a security risk as it involves sharing sensitive information with external entities. In contrast, pull-based deployments do not require exposing credentials externally, enhancing security.",
          "id": "D"
        }
      ],
